# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: august-bebel
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:august-bebel/1890-german-federal-election] A federal election for the eighth Reichstag of the German Empire was held on 20 February 1890.
[src:august-bebel/1890-german-federal-election] It was an early election called after Chancellor Otto von Bismarck requested that the Reichstag elected in February 1887 be dissolved because it had refused to extend the Anti-Socialist Laws.
[src:august-bebel/1890-german-federal-election] He thought that a newly elected Reichstag would be more likely to pass the bill, but the parties that supported him – the German Conservative Party, German Reich Party and National Liberals, known as the Cartel parties – lost 91 seats and their majority in parliament.
[src:august-bebel/1890-german-federal-election] The Centre Party regained its position as the largest party, winning 107 of the 397 seats and 18.6% of the vote, while the National Liberal Party, formerly the largest party, was reduced to 38 seats.
[src:august-bebel/1890-german-federal-election] The Social Democratic Party won the most votes with 19.8%, but that translated to only 35 seats due to the lack of redistricting and the first-past-the-post voting system.
[src:august-bebel/1890-german-federal-election] The previous Reichstag election in 1887 was held early after Emperor Wilhelm I, at Chancellor Otto von Bismarck's request, dissolved the Reichstag when it failed to pass Bismarck's seven-year military budget.
[src:august-bebel/1890-german-federal-election] Bismarck hoped, with good reason, that a new Reichstag would approve the bill.
[src:august-bebel/1890-german-federal-election] The three Cartel parties – the German Conservative Party, German Reich Party (Free Conservatives) and National Liberals – picked up 53 additional seats in the election for a total of 219 out of 397, giving them a 55% majority.
[src:august-bebel/1890-german-federal-election] On 11 March 1887, just a few weeks after the election, the Reichstag approved Bismarck's military budget with the seven-year period he wanted.
[src:august-bebel/1890-german-federal-election] On 9 February 1888, the Reichstag amended the Reich constitution to extend the legislative term from three to five years.
[src:august-bebel/1890-german-federal-election] The move was taken to extend the life of the existing majority coalition and with it Bismarck's ability to govern.
[src:august-bebel/1890-german-federal-election] Wilhelm I died on 9 March 1888 and his son Frederick III, who was gravely ill when he ascended the throne, died on 15 June, leaving the crown to Wilhelm II.
[src:august-bebel/1890-german-federal-election] Unlike his grandfather, Wilhelm II involved himself in day-to-day politics and in doing so came into conflict with Chancellor Bismarck.
[src:august-bebel/1890-german-federal-election] Bismarck's attempt to make the Anti-Socialist Laws permanent was defeated in the Reichstag on 25 January 1890, a failure that was the result of divisions within the Cartel parties.
[src:august-bebel/1890-german-federal-election] Wilhelm immediately dissolved the Reichstag at Bismarck's request even though he disapproved of the Anti-Socialist Laws and wanted to introduce labour protection legislation.
[src:august-bebel/1890-german-federal-election] He was willing to follow Bismarck because he wanted to increase the military budget and knew that Bismarck could help him see it through the Reichstag.
[src:august-bebel/1890-german-federal-election] The election was held under general, equal, direct and secret suffrage.
[src:august-bebel/1890-german-federal-election] All German males over the age of 25 years were able to vote except for active members of the military and recipients of poor relief.
[src:august-bebel/1890-german-federal-election] The restrictions on the military were meant to keep it from becoming politicized, while men on relief were considered to be open to political manipulation.
[src:august-bebel/1890-german-federal-election] The constitutional guarantee of a secret vote was not safeguarded at the time, since ballot boxes and polling booths were not introduced until 1903.
[src:august-bebel/1890-german-federal-election] If no candidate in a district won an absolute majority of the votes, a runoff election was held between the first- and second-place finishers.
[src:august-bebel/1890-german-federal-election] It was possible for a replacement candidate to be introduced in a runoff.
[src:august-bebel/1890-german-federal-election] The election was a major defeat for Bismarck and the Cartel parties, which together lost 91 seats.
[src:august-bebel/1890-german-federal-election] The Centre Party remained the strongest party, winning 106 constituencies (27.2% of seats) with 18.6% of the popular vote.
[src:august-bebel/1890-german-federal-election] The left-liberal parties also made significant gains in votes and representation.
[src:august-bebel/1890-german-federal-election] For the first time, a member of a German party (the SPD) won a seat in Alsace-Lorraine.
[src:august-bebel/1890-german-federal-election] Regionalists made gains off the decline of the Cartel parties.
[src:august-bebel/1890-german-federal-election] Antisemites gained only 0.7% of the votes but won five constituencies.
[src:august-bebel/1890-german-federal-election] Their strongholds were the Grand Duchy of Hesse and Hesse-Nassau.
[src:august-bebel/1890-german-federal-election] The Social Democrats nearly doubled their vote share compared to the 1887 election and won the popular vote for the first time with over 1.4 million votes, or 19.75% of the total.
[src:august-bebel/1890-german-federal-election] From his London exile, Friedrich Engels proclaimed that the day of polling was “the day the German revolution began”.
[src:august-bebel/1890-german-federal-election] In spite of the SPD's popular vote, the party won only 35 seats (8.8% of the 397).
[src:august-bebel/1890-german-federal-election] One of the reasons for the low seat count was that Germany had not redistricted since 1871, when each district had about 100,000 voters.
[src:august-bebel/1890-german-federal-election] In the 20 intervening years, there had been considerable rural to urban migration due to industrialisation.
[src:august-bebel/1890-german-federal-election] The SPD, with its predominantly urban electorate, suffered disproportionately because each vote in a heavily populated urban district carried less weight than a vote in a sparsely populated rural district.
[src:august-bebel/1890-german-federal-election] A second reason was that the German Empire used a first-past-the-post voting system in which a candidate in a district could win in the first round only by obtaining an absolute majority of the votes cast.
[src:august-bebel/1890-german-federal-election] If a second round was necessary, the conservative and national liberal parties generally formed electoral alliances, often against the SPD candidate.
[src:august-bebel/1890-german-federal-election] The SPD seldom entered into such alliances.
[src:august-bebel/1890-german-federal-election] Wilhelm II dismissed Bismarck from office a month after the election and replaced him with Leo von Caprivi.
[src:august-bebel/1890-german-federal-election] The Reichstag allowed the Anti-Socialist Laws to lapse on 30 September 1890.
[src:august-bebel/1907-german-federal-election] Federal elections were held in Germany on 25 January 1907.
[src:august-bebel/1907-german-federal-election] Despite the Social Democratic Party (SPD) receiving a clear plurality of votes, they were hampered by the unequal constituency sizes that favoured rural seats.
[src:august-bebel/1907-german-federal-election] As a result, the Centre Party remained the largest party in the Reichstag after winning 101 of the 397 seats, whilst the SPD won only 43.
[src:august-bebel/1907-german-federal-election] This election was known as the "Hottentot election" due to the scandal over the ongoing genocide of the Khoisan people in German South West Africa.
[src:august-bebel/1907-german-federal-election] The election became known as the "Hottentot Election" because its causes and campaign were dominated by the Herero and Nama genocide in the colony of German South West Africa.
[src:august-bebel/1907-german-federal-election] The Nama were referred to as "Hottentots", a term that was derogatory even at the time.
[src:august-bebel/1907-german-federal-election] The sustained and increasingly expensive colonial war led to a political crisis in Germany on 2 August 1906, when the Government requested an appropriation of 29 million marks from the Reichstag.
[src:august-bebel/1907-german-federal-election] The Social Democratic Party of Germany (SPD), in particular, refused to approve further money given the ruthless conduct of the war with genocidal casualties among the Nama.
[src:august-bebel/1907-german-federal-election] The Government attempted to settle the conflict by making concessions, but soon met opposition from Centre Party representative Matthias Erzberger in particular, who criticised the extensive spending and argued against the colonial wars.
[src:august-bebel/1907-german-federal-election] This led to the Centre Party group, against the will of some of its members, voting against the appropriation.
[src:august-bebel/1907-german-federal-election] On the other hand, the Conservatives and National Liberals were vehemently in favour of continuing the colonial war.
[src:august-bebel/1907-german-federal-election] On the 13th of December, the vote in the Reichstag came down with a narrow majority of 177 to 168 against the appropriation.
[src:august-bebel/1907-german-federal-election] On the same day, Chancellor Bernhard von Bülow ordered the Reichstag dissolved with the agreement of Emperor Wilhelm II.
[src:august-bebel/1907-german-federal-election] One reason for dissolving the legislature over such a minor issue was that the Emperor as well as parts of the bureaucracy had increasing reservations about the Centre Party.
[src:august-bebel/1907-german-federal-election] Bülow, who did not share this position and would have liked to continue relying on the centre, gave in to this.
[src:august-bebel/1907-german-federal-election] He hoped that establishing a new political majority would allow him to restore his damaged trust with the Emperor.
[src:august-bebel/1907-german-federal-election] Under the circumstances, the only way to do this would be to resume the former Cartel Parties alliance between Conservatives and National Liberals, expanded to include the left-liberal parties.
[src:august-bebel/1907-german-federal-election] Following the death of Eugen Richter the previous year, the left-liberals had tended to indicate their willingness to support the Government.
[src:august-bebel/1907-german-federal-election] This alliance came to pass and is generally referred to as the Bülow Bloc.
[src:august-bebel/1907-german-federal-election] Through the mediation of the government, agreements were reached to cooperate during runoff elections, which had now become common.
[src:august-bebel/1907-german-federal-election] The goal was to create a nationalist, anti-socialist and anti-clerical bloc out of the Cartel parties and the left-liberals.
[src:august-bebel/1907-german-federal-election] This was supported by the newly founded National Association Against Social Democracy.
[src:august-bebel/1907-german-federal-election] The SPD gained around a quarter of a million votes compared to 1903, receiving 10% more of the vote than any other party, although the high turnout meant the SPD's vote share in total was down.
[src:august-bebel/1907-german-federal-election] Also affecting the Social Democrats negatively were the runoff agreements between the parties of the bloc.
[src:august-bebel/1907-german-federal-election] So, despite their high share of the vote, they only won 43 seats compared to 81 in 1903.
[src:august-bebel/1907-german-federal-election] The centre were able to make gains, going from 100 to 105 seats.
[src:august-bebel/1907-german-federal-election] The bloc parties made minor seat gains, primarily because their electoral agreements meant they did not compete with each other.
[src:august-bebel/1907-german-federal-election] The two conservative parties increased their seat number from 75 to 84.
[src:august-bebel/1907-german-federal-election] Even more minor were the gains for the National Liberals, who rose from 51 to 54 seats.
[src:august-bebel/1907-german-federal-election] However, the left-liberals made clearer gains, improving their position from 36 to 49 seats.
[src:august-bebel/1907-german-federal-election] In total, when counting minor parties and independents aligned with it, the bloc achieved a majority of 220 out of 397 seats.
[src:august-bebel/1907-german-federal-election] Also notable was the success of Polish candidates in Upper Silesia, winning five out of the region's twelve constituencies.
[src:august-bebel/1907-german-federal-election] This was in contrast to the elections from 1871 to 1898, in which, despite the Polish-speaking majority, no Polish candidate ever won a seat there.
[src:august-bebel/1907-german-federal-election] This politicisation of the Upper Silesian Poles was primarily caused by the anti-Polish linguistic and cultural policies of the Prussian state government (see the Września school strike).
[src:august-bebel/1912-german-federal-election] Federal elections were held in Germany on 12 January 1912.
[src:august-bebel/1912-german-federal-election] Although the Social Democratic Party (SPD) had received the most votes in every election since 1890, it had never won the most seats, and in the 1907 elections, it had won fewer than half the seats won by the Centre Party despite receiving over a million more votes.
[src:august-bebel/1912-german-federal-election] However, the 1912 elections saw the SPD retain its position as the most voted-for party and become the largest party in the Reichstag, winning 110 of the 397 seats.
[src:august-bebel/1912-german-federal-election] Parties hostile or ambivalent to the ruling elites of the German Empire – the Social Democrats, the Centre Party, and the left-liberal Progressives – together won a majority of the seats.
[src:august-bebel/1912-german-federal-election] This allowed a successful censure vote against the government of Theobald von Bethmann Hollweg over the Saverne Affair in 1913 and the passage of the Reichstag Peace Resolution of 1917.
[src:august-bebel/1912-german-federal-election] However, the Centre and the Progressives were unwilling to act consistently in opposition, which left the government largely free to do as it wished.
[src:august-bebel/1912-german-federal-election] Some historians, such as Fritz Fischer, have theorized that the First World War was partly a result of the strategy of the conservative Prussian Junkers to deal with the result.
[src:august-bebel/1912-german-federal-election] In an attempt to increase support for conservative parties and policies and to distract the population from the SPD, they hoped to drum up patriotism in an external conflict with Russia or another Eastern European state such as Serbia.
[src:august-bebel/1912-german-federal-election] Georges Weill, an SPD candidate who won a seat in Metz, defected to France at the start of World War I.
[src:august-bebel/1912-german-federal-election] The members of the Reichstag were elected in single-member constituencies via the two-round system.
[src:august-bebel/1912-german-federal-election] There was no requirement that constituencies had to be of equal sizes population sizes, meaning that rural constituencies, which tended to have smaller populations, were overrepresented.
[src:august-bebel/1912-german-federal-election] Since 1888, a constitutional amendment required elections to be held every five years.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] The **20th Century Press Archives** (German: *Pressearchiv 20.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] Jahrhundert*) comprises about 19 million newspaper clippings, organized in folders about persons, companies, wares, events and topics.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] It originates from the Hamburg Kolonialinstitut (colonial institute) founded in 1908.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] Within the Hamburg Institute of International Economics (HWWA) it turned into a unique public press archive.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] In 2007 it was absorbed by the German National Library of Economics (ZBW) and merged with the Wirtschaftsarchiv (economics archive) of the Kiel Institute for the World Economy (IfW), founded in 1914.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] Article collection was discontinued at the end of 2005, but the archive is still open to the public.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] The archive has its origins in two institutions in the German cities of Hamburg and Kiel.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] In Hamburg, after a few years, the "Zentralstelle" (central office) of the Kolonialinstitut was transformed from a free information center for colonial issues into a comprehensive archive of global political and economic topics, which primarily supported the city's merchants.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] After the breakdown of the German colonial empire in World War I, the renaming to "Hamburgisches Welt-Wirtschafts-Archiv" in 1919 sealed this reorientation.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] The staff of HWWA reflected its importance and grew from 54 in 1919 to 183 permanent or temporary employees in 1958 – a number that seems to have remained largely stable until the late 1990s.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] Founded shortly before the outbreak of the First World War, the Kiel Economic Archive and its library were closely linked to the scientific work of the IfW, which focused on global economic contexts and their practical use.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] In 1966, the library of the IfW was given the function of a central library for economics by the German Research Foundation (DFG) in the Federal Republic of Germany, and in 1993, the department was renamed accordingly.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] During the first and second world wars, both archives were intensively involved in the foreign and wartime planning of the empire and the Nazi state.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] Starting in 1936, "Confidential Reports from the Foreign Press" provided selected economic leaders and Nazi departments with "largely unfiltered information and comments on economic issues from foreign media and represented a unique feature in Nazi media policy".
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] Acting with the informal means of a foreign cultural and information policy supplementing the military expansion policy, HWWA and IfW dedicated their services to the Nazi regime.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] In 1996, a closer cooperation between HWWA and ZBW / Wirtschaftsarchiv began, with the aim of merging the two archives.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] From the beginning of 2001, the articles were indexed according to a new common classification system and made retrievable via a reference database, "EconPress".
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] Following a recommendation from an evaluation within the Leibniz Association in 2003, the current press documentation was finished at the end of 2005 and the materials were frozen at that point.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] The separate existence of the HWWA ended in 2007 with the integration of its press documentation and library into the ZBW as a newly formed foundation under public law.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] Today, the press archive belongs to the (research) organisations of the Leibniz Association.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] By 1919 at the latest, the Hamburg archive collected "press clippings on a global scale".
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] More than 1400 sources were monitored for the press archives.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] Their broad international distribution provides access to the history of political thought and receptive history of the covered topics.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] Occasionally, the collected publications go back as far as 1826.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] While the persons archive was only available in paper form until its partial digitization, the holdings of the topics, wares and companies archives were saved every ten years on roll film or microfiche since the 1960s and then the paper clippings were pulped.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] The holdings of the Kiel Wirtschaftsarchiv are less comprehensively documented.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] The "war archive" of 1914–1918, which amounted to one million clippings, was destroyed by a bomb strike in 1942.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] In 1958, when six scientific experts and more than 30 employees in total were collecting and organizing the material, the total extent of the archive was estimated as more than three million, and in 1993 as more than ten million.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] Jahrhundert* application, parts of the holdings of both archives are now accessible on the web.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] From 2004 to 2007, the German Research Foundation funded a project to digitize parts of the archives, namely the materials from the beginning up to 1949 (the formation of the Federal Republic of Germany).
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] The paper clippings from the folders of the persons archive were scanned, and metadata (folder and document ID as well as page number, occasionally also source, publication date, author and title) were recorded by project staff.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] Optical character recognition could not be applied due to the partially used Fraktur scripts, the constantly changing fonts (as well as languages) in the sequence of the articles, and the sometimes poor quality of the clippings.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] However, the approximately 5,500 person folders created before 1949 are fully accessible online.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] The roll film parts of the archive (up to 1960) have also been digitized.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] As neither the folders nor the documents on these films were separated in a machine-readable fashion, such formal elements could not be automatically derived.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] Instead, the pages had to be "sliced" with specially developed "Slider" software, assembled into documents and folders, and given metadata.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] Only a small part of this labor-intensive process was finished at the end of the project in 2007.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] It is continued today, so that new folders are continually made available via the web application "Pressemappe 20.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] Jahrhundert", which was created within the framework of the project.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] 11,000 company folders on digitized roll film, by 2018 about 7,500 were accessible online.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] For the topics and wares archives, the proportion of online folders seems to be significantly lower.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] The persons are alphabetically indexed by name, while the companies are accessible by name, geographically by their headquarters and via industry lists.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] The topics can be accessed via the topics hierarchy and country system as well as through a search for subject and geographical GND keywords, and via a world map with geolocations.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] The limitation to 1949 was made for capacity reasons, and due to intellectual property rights restrictions.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] Numerous individual articles within the dossiers are subject to blocking notices if the death of the author (or in the case of anonymous or pseudonymous works, the date of publication) is less than 70 years ago.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] With a moving wall more and more documents should be released over time.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] How many of the about 5.7 million documents digitized in the context of the project are accessible to the scientific and general public on the web is not known.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] In 2019, the German National Library of Economics (ZBW) placed all the metadata of the archives under a CC0 licence, and began a cooperation and "data donation" with Wikimedia Deutschland.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] This led to the creation of many new Wikidata items and the enrichment of many existing items; by the end of 2022, every folder in the archive was connected to items in Wikidata.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] In 2024, changes to intellectual property rights in Europe made it possible to provide complete digitized images from the archive – some 3.8 million pages – for online viewing within the European Union.
[src:august-bebel/20th-century-press-archives] A volunteer project is working on adding links to the archive's folders in Wikidata, so that Wikidata provides an index to the material.
[src:august-bebel/adolf-hepner] Adolf Hepner was born on November 24, 1846, in Schmiegel, Posen (modern day Śmigiel, Poland).
[src:august-bebel/adolf-hepner] He went to the gymnasium school in Lissa (modern day Leszno) before his stint in a Breslau Rabbinical seminary.
[src:august-bebel/adolf-hepner] He attended college at the University of Breslau (modern day University of Wrocław) before he went to college at the University of Berlin.
[src:august-bebel/adolf-hepner] In 1868, Hepner began to become a socialist and he moved on to Leipzig where became an editor for a socialistic paper.
[src:august-bebel/adolf-hepner] He was associated with Wilhelm Liebknecht and August Bebel around his time at the paper.
[src:august-bebel/adolf-hepner] In 1872 he was tried for high treason and soon acquitted with his treason charges stemming from Hepner promoting socialist activities through journalism.
[src:august-bebel/adolf-hepner] His co defendants, Liebknecht and Bebel weren't acquitted like he was.
[src:august-bebel/adolf-hepner] Later that year, Hepner violated Leipzig police director Ruder's prohibition when he visited the International Workers' Congress of the International Workers Association.
[src:august-bebel/adolf-hepner] Hepner took a delegate with him as he met Karl Marx and some similar people whom he knew personally as he got ready for his speech.
[src:august-bebel/adolf-hepner] On September 6, 1872, at The Hague, Hepner made a speech in support of German workers where he expressed his views on how the lack of authority felled the commune.
[src:august-bebel/adolf-hepner] Hepner was put in jail not too long after in part due to Hepner offending the chief constable but he was soon released.
[src:august-bebel/adolf-hepner] Back at the Der Volksstaat, Hepner's rocky relationship with Theodor Yorck eventually led to Hepner being let go of his role at the paper.
[src:august-bebel/adolf-hepner] Hepner moved to Breslau after he was forced out of Leipsic and subsequently he began a failed job as a publisher for his A.
[src:august-bebel/adolf-hepner] Louis in 1886 after emigrating to the United States four years earlier due to the oppression he faced there as a socialist.
[src:august-bebel/adolf-hepner] He got back into editing as he was an editor for the *St.
[src:august-bebel/adolf-hepner] Louis Tageblatt* where he worked for ten years from 1888 to 1898.
[src:august-bebel/adolf-hepner] He was also hired to edit the Westliche Post, where he worked for some years.
[src:august-bebel/adolf-hepner] Hepner went back to Germany in 1908, where he became a writer for the Die Neue Zeit, Süddeutsche Monatshefte and similar publications.
[src:august-bebel/adolf-hepner] Hepner wrote various political essays like *America's Aid to Germany in 1870-1871* in 1904 and other works like a one act play titled *Good Night, Schatz* in 1894.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Politically, it was the only subdivision of the German Empire considered an "Imperial Territory"; as such, it was under the direct administration of the Imperial German state, rather than a quasi-sovereign constituent of the federal Empire.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] It was granted a legislature and limited internal autonomy in 1911.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The territory encompassed almost all of Alsace (93%) and over a quarter of Lorraine (26%), while the rest of these regions remained parts of France.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] For historical reasons, specific legal dispositions are still applied in the territory in the form of a "local law in Alsace–Moselle".
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Due to its special legal status since reversion to France, the territory has been referred to administratively as **Alsace–Moselle** (Alsatian: *Elsàss–Mosel*; German: *Elsaß–Mosel* or *Elsass–Mosel*).
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Since 2016, the historical territory has been part of the French administrative region of Grand Est.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Alsace–Lorraine had a land area of 14,496 km2 (5,597 sq mi).
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The modern history of Alsace–Lorraine was primarily influenced by the rivalry between French and German nationalism.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] France long sought, strategically, to attain and preserve what it considered its "natural boundaries"—the Pyrenees to the southwest, the Alps to the southeast, and the Rhine to the northeast; these strategic aims led to its annexing territories in the Holy Roman Empire west of the Rhine.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] What is now known as Alsace was progressively conquered by France under Louis XIII and Louis XIV in the 17th century, Strasbourg being conquered in 1681, while Lorraine was incorporated from the 16th century under Henry II to the 18th century under Louis XV.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] (in the case of the Three Bishoprics, as early as 1552).
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] These border changes at the time meant more or less that one ruler (the local princes and city governments, with some remaining power of the Holy Roman Emperor) was exchanged for another (the King of France).
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] German nationalism, on the other hand, which in its 19th century form originated as a reaction against the French occupation of large areas of Germany under Napoleon, sought to unify all the German-speaking populations of the former Holy Roman Empire into a single nation-state.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] As various German dialects were spoken by most of the population of Alsace and Moselle (northern Lorraine), these regions were viewed by German nationalists to be rightfully part of a hoped-for united Germany in the future, despite what the French parts of their population wanted.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] In 1871, the newly created German Empire's demand for Alsace from France after its victory in the Franco-Prussian War was not simply a punitive measure.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The transfer was controversial even among the Germans: The German chancellor, Otto von Bismarck, was initially opposed to it, as he thought (correctly) that it would engender permanent French hostility toward Germany.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Some German industrialists did not want the competition from Alsatian industries, such as the cloth makers who would be exposed to competition from the sizeable industry in Mulhouse.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] "If Alsace and Lorraine are taken, then France will later make war on Germany in conjunction with Russia.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Bismarck and the South German industrialists proposed to have Alsace ceded to Switzerland, while Switzerland would compensate Germany with another territory.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The Swiss rejected the proposal, preferring to remain neutral between the French and Germans.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The German Emperor, Wilhelm I, eventually sided with army commander Helmuth von Moltke, other Prussian generals and other officials who argued that a westward shift in the French border was necessary for strategic military and ethnographic reasons.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] From a linguistic perspective, the transfer involved people who for the most part spoke Alemannic German dialects.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] At the time, ethnic identity was often based primarily on language, unlike today's more multifaceted approach focusing on self-identification.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] From a military perspective, by early 1870s standards, shifting the frontier away from the Rhine would give the Germans a strategic buffer against feared future French attacks.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Due to the annexation, the Germans gained control of the fortifications of Metz and Strasbourg (Strassburg) on the left bank of the Rhine and most of the iron resources of Lorraine.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The Imperial Territory (*Reichsland*) created on 28 June 1871 was therefore treated initially as an occupied territory and administered directly by an imperial governor (*Oberpräsident*) appointed by Wilhelm I.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Although it was not technically part of the Kingdom of Prussia, in practical terms, it amounted to the same thing since the emperor was also king of Prussia and the chancellor its minister-president.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Memory of the Napoleonic Wars was still alive in the 1870s.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Wilhelm I himself had had to flee with the Prussian royal family to East Prussia as a nine-year-old in 1806 and had served in the Battle of Waterloo.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Until the Franco-Prussian War, the French had maintained a long-standing desire to establish their entire eastern frontier on the Rhine.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Thus, most 19th-century Germans viewed them as aggressive and acquisitive people.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] In the years before 1870, the Germans feared the French more than the French feared the Germans.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Many Germans at the time thought that the unification of Germany as the new Empire would in itself be enough to earn permanent French enmity and thus desired a defensible border with their long-standing enemy.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Any additional hostility earned from territorial concessions was downplayed as marginal and insignificant in the scheme.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The annexed area consisted of the northern part of Lorraine and Alsace.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The remaining two-thirds of the département of Meurthe and the westernmost one-fifth of Moselle, which had escaped German annexation, were joined to form the new French *département* of Meurthe-et-Moselle.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] In 1900, 11.6% of the population of Alsace–Lorraine spoke French as their first language (11.0% in 1905, 10.9% in 1910).
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] That small francophone areas were affected was used in France to denounce the new border, since Germany had justified the annexation on linguistic grounds.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Under the provisions of the Treaty of Frankfurt, the inhabitants of the annexed areas received Alsace–Lorraine citizenship unless they had migrated directly from France.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Until 1 October 1872, they had the option of retaining French citizenship.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] A total of 160,878 people, or about 10.4% of the total population, took the option.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The proportion was particularly high in Upper Alsace, where 93,109 people (20.3%) declared that they wished to retain French citizenship, and much lower in Lower Alsace (6.5%) and Lorraine (5.8%).
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Originally it was envisaged that those who chose French citizenship would have to leave Alsace–Lorraine.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] They were allowed to either take their property with them or sell it.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Ultimately only about 50,000 people left for France, corresponding to 3.2% of the population of Alsace–Lorraine.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The approximately 110,000 optants who had not emigrated by 1 October 1872 lost their option of French citizenship, although they were not expelled by the German authorities but retained German citizenship.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Some estimates of the total number of optants, however, are as high as 280,000, with the number who left for France set at about 130,000.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] After the Franco-Prussian War, Alsace–Lorraine was directly annexed to the German Empire as an imperial territory and was not a state in its own right.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] It was not until the decree of Emperor Wilhelm I on 29 October 1874 that a popular representation was established, the Territorial Committee (*Landesausschuss*).
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The members of the Territorial Committee were not elected by the people but appointed by the district assemblies (*Bezirkstagen*).
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The three district assemblies for Lorraine, Upper Alsace and Lower Alsace each appointed ten members.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] In 1879 the Territorial Committee was enlarged to 58 members who were indirectly elected by the district assemblies (Lorraine 11, Upper Alsace 10, Lower Alsace 13), the autonomous cities (1 member each from Strassburg, Mülhausen, Metz and Colmar) and the counties (20 members).
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Initially the Territorial Committee had only an advisory function.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] In 1877 it was granted a legislative function and the right to create a budget.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] From 1879 it was allowed to initiate legislation, although the Bundesrat in Berlin had to approve the laws before they were formally enacted by the emperor.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Also in 1879, the office of imperial governor in Alsace–Lorraine (*Reichsstatthalter*) was introduced.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] He represented the Imperial Territory on behalf of the emperor.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The state secretary of the Imperial Office for Alsace–Lorraine headed the government of the Territory.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] On 22 June 1877, Eduard von Moeller, the first governor of Alsace–Lorraine, decreed that 90 place names in the district of Lorraine were to be changed from their French to the German forms.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] When the constitution of the Imperial Territory of Alsace–Lorraine of 31 May 1911 was enacted, a directly elected state parliament (*Landtag*) replaced the Territorial Committee.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Alsace–Lorraine was granted its own constitution, a freely elected parliament and three representatives in the Bundesrat, the German federal council.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Since the Bundesrat represented the interests of the states in Berlin, the members from each state were required to vote as a bloc.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] In Alsace–Lorraine, the governor determined how its three representatives voted.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The votes were not counted if they gave an otherwise defeated Prussian motion a majority.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The introduction of an upper house in parliament was criticized across party lines in Alsace–Lorraine.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] While upper houses had historical reasons in the other parts of Germany, there was no noble class in Alsace–Lorraine to be integrated in an upper house.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The emperor's right to appoint members was particularly criticised.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The upper house was composed of representatives of the major religious communities (Catholics, Lutherans, Protestant Reformed and Jews), the chambers of agriculture and commerce, the trade unions, the judiciary, the cities of Strassburg, Metz, Mülhausen and Colmar, and the University of Strassburg.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] There were also 18 members appointed by the emperor at the recommendation of the Bundesrat.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The lower house consisted of 60 deputies who were elected for a term of three years by majority vote in the 60 electoral districts.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] It was called the "People's Parliament" (*Volksparlament*) in distinction to the upper house, which consisted of notables.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Male citizens aged 25 and over had the right to vote.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] For the late nineteenth century, the constitution was both conservative in defining the first chamber and progressive in the universal and equal manhood suffrage for electing the second chamber.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The representation of trade unions in the first chamber was also remarkable since they were not yet legally recognized as workers' representatives.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The first and only elections to the parliament of the Imperial Territory took place on 22 and 29 October 1911.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The strongest parties were the Alsatian Centre and the Social Democrats with 31.0% and 23.8% of the vote respectively, followed by the Lorraine Autonomists with 16.3%.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] In 1874, Alsace–Lorraine was granted 15 seats in the German Reichstag.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Between 6 and 10 of the 15 Alsatian–Lorraine deputies elected in each of the Reichstag elections from 1874 through 1887 were counted as "Protest Deputies" because of their opposition to the annexation.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The population was also not asked for its opinion on state affiliation in 1918 when it returned to France.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The Protesters rejected both cooperation with the German authorities and constructive political work in the Reichstag.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] They did not attend its sessions after their election (some Lorraine deputies were not able to do so because of their lack of command of German).
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] There were also people in political life who, for various motives, pleaded for an "attitude of reason".
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The so-called Autonomists were more or less either pro-German or pro-French and strove for a local autonomy of the Imperial Territory that was as far-reaching as possible.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The Protestant minority population voted predominantly for the Autonomists from the 1877 Reichstag election onwards.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Over time, however, the population of Alsace–Lorraine turned more and more to the German parties, such as Catholics to the Centre Party, the Protestant bourgeoisie to the Liberals and Conservatives, and the emerging working class to the Social Democrats.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The Protesters no longer played a significant role after the election of 1890.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The majority of Alsace–Lorraine's inhabitants were sceptical of the German Empire during the first two decades and voted for regional parties (Alsace–Lorraine Protesters and Autonomists).
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] After Chancellor Bismarck's dismissal in 1890, the party landscape loosened, and parties of the Empire (Social Democrats, Centre, National Liberals, Left Liberals and Conservatives) found more and more supporters.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] In the countryside and the predominantly French-speaking electoral districts of Lorraine, the Autonomists remained strong, while in the cities, especially Strassburg, they increasingly played only a subordinate role, with the Social Democrats dominating.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The flag used officially in the Imperial Territory was the black-white-red flag of the German Empire.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] A modified imperial service flag of the Foreign Office was adopted on 29 December 1892 for use at state institutions in Alsace–Lorraine.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] It was the imperial tri-colour with the imperial eagle in the centre and the crowned escutcheon of Alsace–Lorraine in the upper left corner.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] On 25 June 1912, the parliament of the Imperial Territory unanimously approved the proposal for a state flag consisting of the red and white striped flag of Alsace bearing a yellow Lorraine cross in the upper left corner.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The decision to adopt the flag was never implemented by government authorities in Berlin.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The flag was often raised privately and on semi-official occasions.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] It was not welcomed by German authorities and the military but was tolerated in part even in wartime.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Unofficially, the traditional red and white territorial flag was popular in Alsace and was often used decoratively and as a postcard motif.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] It was also sometimes taken as a sign of protest against the German annexation.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] In the decades after 1871, the fortress of Metz was expanded under German rule to become the largest fortification in the world, with a ring of outworks, some of which were located far in advance of the fortifications themselves.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Metz became a majority German-speaking city due to the influx of military personnel and other immigrants from the rest of Germany.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] When the German Army was formed after the foundation of the Empire, the XV Prussian Army Corps was created from existing troops.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The corps' district was the new "Border Region" Alsace–Lorraine, as was that of the XVI Army Corps, which was formed in 1890.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The southern regions of the Imperial Territory belonged to the districts of the XIV Army Corps, which was made up in 1871 of troops from Baden.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] From 1912, the northeastern regions belonged to the XXI Army Corps.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The recruiting districts of the corps were outside Alsace–Lorraine, as was the case with the Upper and Lower Alsatian and Lorraine regiments that were established later within the corps as part of army enlargements.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The corps were not always stationed in the Imperial Territory.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Alsatians and Lorrainers who were called up for military service were distributed among all Prussian Army units, as were active and passive social democrats, who were also considered to be politically unreliable.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] It was not until 1903 that a quarter of Alsatian recruits were assigned on a trial basis to troops stationed in their native region.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] In 1910, 4.3% of the local population – about 80,000 men – were military personnel, which made Alsace–Lorraine the region in Germany with the highest concentration of troops.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] At the end of 1913, protests broke out in the Alsatian town of Zabern, where two battalions of Prussian infantry were stationed.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] A young German lieutenant insulted the Alsatian population in a speech to soldiers and called for rebellious Alsatians to be stabbed.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] In what came to be known as the Zabern Affair, the military reacted to the protests with arbitrary acts that were not covered by law.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The assaults led to a Reichstag debate on the militaristic structures of German society and strained the relations between Alsace–Lorraine and the rest of Germany.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Planning began in 1871 for a strategic railway line from Berlin to Metz in order to integrate the new Imperial Territory militarily and strategically.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The "cannon railway" was completed in the 1870s.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The railways of the private French Eastern Railway Company (*Compagnie des Chemins de Fer de l'Est*) – a total of 740 km of lines – were bought by the French state and then sold to Germany for 260 million gold marks.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The purchase price was offset against the war compensation to be paid by France.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The Imperial Railways in Alsace–Lorraine was the first railway owned by the German Reich.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Until the First World War, the Imperial Territory experienced a great economic boom, and many new socio-political benefits such as social security and health insurance were introduced in line with developments in the rest of the German Empire.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] In 1872, the University of Strassburg was re-founded and in 1877 given the name "Emperor Wilhelm University" (after Emperor Wilhelm I).
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Through generous expansion measures, it developed into one of the largest universities in the Empire.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Professional training in Alsace developed as a result of stimuli from Germany.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The German administration promoted the education of young Alsatian artists at German universities and academies, giving rise to the Cercle de Saint-Léonard, an artists' association that sought to combine German and Alsatian art.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Although the proportion of native speakers of German dialects in the new Imperial Territory was around 90%, Catholics in Alsace–Lorraine tended initially to be sceptical about the ethnographic unification with Germany, which had come about under the leadership of predominately Protestant Prussia.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] While the Catholics frequently identified with the French Catholic state and feared disadvantage in Prussian hands, the local Protestants were in favour of becoming part of Germany.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The Evangelical Lutheran Church professed allegiance to Germany, hoping to reduce French-influenced Catholic "paternalism".
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The rural population in particular supported their efforts, while quite a few critics of unification spoke out in the cities of Strassburg and Mülhausen.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] After the *Kulturkampf* – the conflict between the state and the Catholic Church driven by Chancellor Otto von Bismarck – reached Alsace–Lorraine in 1872/73, the Catholic Church became a vehicle of resistance against the German authorities.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] In all of the Reichstag elections from 1874 to 1912, between three and seven of the 15 Alsace–Lorraine deputies were Catholic priests.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The dispute reached a climax when, on 3 August 1873, a pastoral letter from the Bishop of Nancy-Toul calling for prayers for the reunification of Alsace–Lorraine with France was read in the Alsace–Lorraine districts of Château-Salins and Saarburg, which still belonged to his diocese.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The German authorities reacted with police measures, arrests and disciplinary proceedings as well as a ban on the Catholic press.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] After the beginning of the 20th century, opposition to German authorities played hardly any role.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] There were no longer major social groups that advocated a return to France.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The Protestants traditionally had a positive image of Germany, while after the Dreyfus affair the Jewish population regarded France with extreme suspicion.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The rise of socialism there permanently unsettled Catholic sentiments in Alsace–Lorraine, and France's laicist policy from 1905 onwards (Law on the Separation of the Churches and the State) also led to Catholic alienation from France.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Germany had granted the region significantly more freedom, and the region's economic situation had developed positively.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The younger inhabitants, who had had no contact with France, especially saw themselves as Germans as a matter of course.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] In French foreign policy, the demand for the return of Alsace and Lorraine faded in importance after 1880 with the decline of the French monarchist element, but when World War I broke out in 1914, recovery of the two lost provinces became the top French war goal.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The increased militarization of Europe and the lack of negotiations between major powers led to harsh and rash actions regarding Alsace–Lorraine being taken by both sides during World War I.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] As soon as war was declared, both the French and German authorities used the inhabitants of Alsace–Lorraine as propaganda pawns.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Germans living in France were arrested and placed into camps by French authorities.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] When the French army occupied certain villages, veterans on the German side of the 1870 conflict were sought out and arrested.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The Germans responded to the outbreak of war with harsh measures against the Alsace–Lorraine populace.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The Zabern Affair had convinced the high command that the population was hostile to the German Empire and that it should be forced into submission.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The German military feared that French partisans – called *francs-tireurs* during the Franco-Prussian War – would reappear.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] German authorities developed policies aimed at reducing the influence of French.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] In Metz, street names had been sign-posted in French and German; French was suppressed in January 1915.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] On 15 July 1915, German became the only official language in the region, leading to the Germanization of towns' names from 2 September 1915.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Prohibiting the speaking of French in public further increased the exasperation of some of the natives, who were long accustomed to mixing their conversation with French language; the use of even one word, as innocent as "bonjour", could incur a fine.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Some ethnic Germans in the region cooperated in the persecution as a way to demonstrate German patriotism.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] German authorities became increasingly worried about renewed French nationalism.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] About 15,000 Alsatians and Lorrainers served in the German Navy.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The soviet councils disbanded themselves with the departure of the German troops between 16 and 20 November.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The arrival of the French Army stabilized the situation: French troops put the region under military occupation and entered Strasbourg on 22 November.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The *Nationalrat* proclaimed the annexation of Alsace to France on 5 December.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The Soviet Republic came to an end, but the annexation was not internationally recognized until the Treaty of Versailles was concluded in 1919.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] France divided Alsace–Lorraine into the *départements* of Haut-Rhin, Bas-Rhin, and Moselle, the same political structure as before the annexation and as created by the French Revolution, but with slightly different limits.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Even today, laws in the three regions are somewhat different from the rest of France.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The specific provisions in force are known as the *local law in Alsace–Moselle*.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The *département* Meurthe-et-Moselle was maintained even after France recovered Alsace–Lorraine in 1919.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The area of Belfort became a special status area and was not reintegrated into Haut-Rhin in 1919, but instead was made a full status *département* in 1922 under the name Territoire-de-Belfort.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The French government immediately started a Francization campaign that included the forced deportation of all Germans who had settled in the area after 1870.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] For that purpose, the population was divided in four categories: A (French citizens before 1870), B (their descendants), C (citizens of Allied or neutral states), and D (enemy aliens—Germans).
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] By July 1921, 111,915 people categorized as "D" were expelled to Germany.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] All place names were gallicized (e.g., Strassburg → Strasbourg, Mülhausen → Mulhouse, Schlettstadt → Sélestat, etc.).
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] On 1 September 1939, the day World War II started, residents of Alsace and Moselle living in the Franco-German border region were evacuated.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] This comprised about one third of the population of Alsace and Moselle, or about 600,000 residents.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The evacuation was aimed at providing space for military operations and for protecting citizens from attack.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The evacuees were allowed to return in July 1940, after France surrendered to Germany.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The area then came under German occupation.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Nazi laws against homosexuality were applied to Alsace–Moselle, and homosexuals were deported.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The Nazis also deported refugee and resident Jews, mostly to concentration camps.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] After the defeat of France in the spring of 1940, Alsace and Moselle were not formally annexed by Nazi Germany, which nonetheless exercised *de facto* control.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Although the terms of the armistice specified that the integrity of the whole French territory could not be modified in any way, Adolf Hitler, the German *Führer*, drafted an annexation law in 1940 that he kept secret, expecting to announce it in the event of a German victory.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Alsace and Moselle were each placed under a Chief of Civil Administration (CdZ), who was the Nazi Party *Gauleiter* and *Reichsstatthalter* (Reich Governor) of the adjacent German territory.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Alsace was administered as part of Gau Baden under Robert Heinrich Wagner and his deputy, Hermann Röhn.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Moselle was administered as part of the Gau Saarpfalz, (later Gau Westmark) under Josef Bürckel and his deputy, Ernst Ludwig Leyser.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Beginning in 1942, people from Alsace and Moselle were made German citizens by decree of the Nazi government.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Beginning in October 1942, young Alsatian and Lorrainian men were conscripted into the German armed forces.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Sometimes they were known as the *malgré-nous*, which could be translated into English as "against our will".
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] A small minority volunteered, notably the author of *The Forgotten Soldier*, known by the pseudonym Guy Sajer.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Ultimately 100,000 Alsatians and 30,000 Mosellans were enrolled, many of them to fight against the Soviet Red Army, on Germany's eastern front.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Most of those who survived the war were interned in Tambov in Russia in 1945.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Many others fought in Normandy against the Allies as the *malgré-nous* of the 2nd SS Panzer Division Das Reich, some of whom were involved in the Oradour sur Glane and Tulle war crimes.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The German-linked Alsatian dialect remains the lingua franca of the region, although perhaps used more by older people.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Both French and German are taught in the schools.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] When Alsace and the Lorraine department became part of Germany, the French laws regarding religious bodies were preserved, with special privileges to the then recognised religions of Calvinism, Judaism, Lutheranism and Roman Catholicism, under a system known as the Concordat.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] However, the Roman Catholic dioceses of Metz and of Strasbourg became exempt jurisdictions.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The Church of Augsburg Confession of France, with its directory, supreme consistory and the bulk of its parishioners residing in Alsace, was reorganised as the Protestant Church of Augsburg Confession of Alsace and Lorraine (EPCAAL) in 1872, but territorially confined to Alsace–Lorraine only.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The five local Calvinist consistories, originally part of the Reformed Church of France, formed a statewide synod in 1895, the Protestant Reformed Church of Alsace and Lorraine (EPRAL).
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] The three Israelite consistories in Colmar, Metz and Strasbourg were disentangled from supervision by the Israelite Central Consistory of France and continued as separate statutory corporations which never formed a joint body, but cooperated.
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] All the mentioned religious bodies retained the status as *établissements publics de culte* (public bodies of religion).
[src:august-bebel/alsace-lorraine] Both Germanic and Romance dialects were traditionally spoken in Alsace–Lorraine before the 20th century.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] German individualist philosopher Max Stirner became an important early influence in anarchism.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] Afterwards Johann Most became an important anarchist propagandist in both Germany and in the United States.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] In the late 19th century and early 20th century there appeared individualist anarchists influenced by Stirner such as John Henry Mackay, Adolf Brand and Anselm Ruest (Ernst Samuel) and Mynona (Salomo Friedlaender).
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] The anarchists Gustav Landauer, Silvio Gesell and Erich Mühsam had important leadership positions within the revolutionary councilist structures during the uprising at the late 1910s known as Bavarian Soviet Republic.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] During the rise of Nazi Germany, Erich Mühsam was assassinated in a Nazi concentration camp both for his anarchist positions and for his Jewish background.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] The anarcho-syndicalist activist and writer Rudolf Rocker became an influential personality in the establishment of the international federation of anarcho-syndicalist organizations called International Workers' Association as well as the Free Workers' Union of Germany.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] Contemporary German anarchist organizations include the anarcho-syndicalist Free Workers' Union and the Federation of German speaking Anarchists (Föderation Deutschsprachiger AnarchistInnen).
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] Historians often trace the roots of German anarchism back to the 16th century German Peasants' War, though historians of anarchism James Joll and George Woodcock hold that this link is exaggerated.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] The liberal thinking of Friedrich Schiller, Johann Wolfgang von Goethe, Gotthold Ephraim Lessing, and Heinrich Heine is also held as a precursor to German anarchism, as well as the anarchist tendencies of several German socialists of this period.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] Karl Grün, well known for his role in the disputes between Marx and Proudhon, held a view historian Max Nettlau would liken to communist anarchism while still living in Cologne and then left for Paris, where he became a disciple of Proudhon.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] Wilhelm Marr, born in Hamburg but primarily active in the *Young Germany* clubs in Switzerland, edited several antiauthoritarian periodicals.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] In his book on anarchism *Anarchie oder Autorität*, he comes to the conclusion that liberty is found only in anarchy.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] German anarchists such as Nettlau and Gustav Landauer credited Edgar Bauer with founding the anarchist tradition in Germany.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] As the 1860s drew to a close, Johann Most was won over to the ideas of the emerging international socialism movement.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] Most saw in the doctrines of Karl Marx and Ferdinand Lassalle a blueprint for a new egalitarian society and became a fervent supporter of the Social Democracy, as the Marxist movement was known in the day.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] After advocating violent action, including the use of explosive bombs, as a mechanism to bring about revolutionary change, Most was forced into exile by the government.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] He went to France but was forced to leave at the end of 1878, settling in London.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] There he founded his own newspaper, *Freiheit* (Freedom), in 1879.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] Convinced by his own experience of the futility of parliamentary action, Most began to espouse the doctrine of anarchism, which led to his expulsion from the German Social Democratic Party in 1880.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] The philosophy of Max Stirner, a German, is usually called "egoism" and rejects political systems in favor of living without regard to others.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] Stirner held that the only limitation on the rights of the individual is his power to obtain what he desires without regard for God, state, or morality.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] He proposes that most commonly accepted social institutions—including the notion of State, property as a right, natural rights in general, and the very notion of society—were figments (*spooks*) in the mind.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] Stirner wanted to abolish both state and societal responsibility for its people.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] Stirner's egoism and *The Ego and Its Own* (1844) were foundational to the development of individualist anarchism.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] The philosophy of Friedrich Nietzsche, A German individualist held many Anarchist ideas and was in favor of more radical ways to personal liberation.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] The Scottish-born John Henry Mackay became Germany's most important individualist anarchist propagandist.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] He fused Stirnerist egoism with the positions of Benjamin Tucker and translated Tucker into German.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] Two semi-fictional writings of his own *Die Anarchisten* and *Der Freiheitsucher* contributed to individualist theory, updating egoist themes with respect to the anarchist movement.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] His writing were translated into English as well.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] The German Stirnerite and pioneer campaigner for male bisexuality and homosexuality, Adolf Brand, published the world's first ongoing homosexual publication, *Der Eigene*, in 1896.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] In the German uprising known as the Bavarian Soviet Republic the anarchists Gustav Landauer, Silvio Gesell and Erich Mühsam had important leadership positions within the revolutionary councilist structures.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] Rudolf Rocker returned to Germany in November 1918 upon an invitation from Fritz Kater to re-build the Free Association of German Trade Unions (FVdG).
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] The FVdG was a radical labor federation that quit the SPD in 1908 and became increasingly syndicalist and anarchist.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] During World War I, it had been unable to continue its activities for fear of government repression, but remained in existence as an underground organization.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] Rocker was opposed to the FVdG's alliance with the communists during and immediately after the November Revolution, as he rejected Marxism, especially the concept of the dictatorship of the proletariat.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] The FVdG grew rapidly and the coalition with the communists soon began to crumble.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] Syndicalist members of the Communist Party were expelled.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] The program only recognized de-centralized, purely economic organizations.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] On Gustav Landauer's death during the Munich Soviet Republic uprising, Rocker took over the work of editing the German publications of Kropotkin's writings.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] In 1920, the social democratic Defense Minister Gustav Noske started the suppression of the revolutionary left, which led to the imprisonment of Rocker and Fritz Kater.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] During their mutual detainment, Rocker convinced Kater, who had still held some social democratic ideals, completely of anarchism.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] In the following years, Rocker became one of the most regular writers in the FAUD organ *Der Syndikalist*.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] The FAUD hosted an international syndicalist conference in 1920 that led to the founding of the International Workers' Association (IWA) in December 1922.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] Augustin Souchy, Alexander Schapiro, and Rocker became the organization's secretaries and Rocker wrote its platform.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] Germany's syndicalist movement declined in the mid-1920s.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] The FAUD reached its peak of around 150,000 members in 1921 before losing members to both the Communist and the Social Democratic Party.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] In the 1930 elections, the Nazi Party received 18.3% of all votes, a total of 6 million.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] Rocker was worried: "Once the Nazis get to power, we'll all go the way of Landauer and Eisner" (who were killed by reactionaries in the course of the Munich Soviet Republic uprising).
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] Rocker left Germany after the Reichstag fire, receiving news of Erich Mühsam's arrest as they left.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] After World War II, an appeal in the *Fraye Arbeter Shtime* detailed the plight of German anarchists and called for Americans to support them.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] By February 1946, the sending of aid parcels to anarchists in Germany was a large-scale operation.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] In 1947, Rocker published *Zur Betrachting der Lage in Deutschland* (*Regarding the Portrayal of the Situation in Germany*) about the impossibility of another anarchist movement in Germany.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] It became the first post-World War II anarchist writing to be distributed in Germany.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] Rocker thought young Germans were all either totally cynical or inclined to fascism and awaited a new generation to grow up before anarchism could bloom once again in the country.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] Nevertheless, the Federation of Libertarian Socialists (FFS) was founded in 1947 by former FAUD members.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] Rocker wrote for its organ, *Die Freie Gesellschaft*, which survived until 1953.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] East Germany carried out hundreds of arrests against anarcho-syndicalists in 1948-49, the leader Wilhelm Jelinek was murdered in prison in 1952.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] German authorities have tried to evict anarchist communities and squats that are the base of anarchist support.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] During the 2020 pandemic German authorities forcefully evicted Liebig 34, an anarchist autonomous zone.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] This resulted in clashes with police and riots, as well as large demonstrations in support of Liebig 34.
[src:august-bebel/anarchism-in-germany] Residents of Liebig 34 were later forcefully removed by German police.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] Born into poverty in Prussia, Bebel was orphaned at a young age and apprenticed as a woodturner.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] His experiences as a traveling journeyman exposed him to the hardships of the working class and led him to socialist politics in the 1860s.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] With Wilhelm Liebknecht, he was a founder of the Social Democratic Workers' Party of Germany (SDAP) in 1869, which in 1875 merged with the General German Workers' Association to form what would become the SPD.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] Bebel became a central figure in the German socialist movement, opposing the nationalist and state-oriented socialism of Ferdinand Lassalle in favor of a more orthodox Marxist, internationalist position.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] During the Franco-Prussian War, he gained notoriety for his opposition to the annexation of Alsace-Lorraine, which led to his conviction for high treason in 1872.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] During the era of the Anti-Socialist Laws (1878–1890), when the SPD was outlawed, Bebel became the party's central figure, guiding it through years of persecution from both within Germany and from exile in Switzerland.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] He was instrumental in maintaining party unity, purging anarchist influences, and establishing the party's official newspaper, *Der Sozialdemokrat*.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] After the repeal of the laws in 1890, Bebel oversaw the SPD's transformation into a mass party, helping to draft its influential Erfurt Program in 1891.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] In his later years, he defended the party's orthodox Marxist principles against the revisionist theories of Eduard Bernstein while simultaneously pursuing a pragmatic, reformist course in the Reichstag.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] His work, particularly his influential 1879 book *Woman and Socialism*, established him as a leading figure in the socialist movement's advocacy for women's rights.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] By the time of his death in 1913, Bebel was revered by the German working class and recognized internationally as a major political figure.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] His funeral in Zurich was a major international event, attended by leaders of the Second International.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] He left behind a party that had grown into the largest in Germany, and his legacy influenced the course of both West and East German politics in the 20th century.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] Ferdinand August Bebel was born on 22 February 1840 in Deutz, a garrison town across the Rhine from Cologne in the Prussian Rhine Province.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] His father, Johann Gottlob Bebel, was a Prussian non-commissioned officer from the region of Posen, while his mother, Wilhelmina Johanna Simon, was a servant girl and the daughter of a cooper from Wetzlar.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] The family lived in impoverished conditions in a single room within a fortress casemate.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] Both of Bebel's parents died of tuberculosis; his father died in 1844, and his mother in 1853.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] After his father's death, his mother remarried his father's twin brother, Ferdinand August Bebel, who was also a soldier and died of tuberculosis in 1846.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] Orphaned at the age of thirteen, Bebel and his brother Julius were left penniless.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] He was taken into the care of an aunt in Wetzlar, where he completed his elementary schooling (*Volksschule*) in 1854.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] Lacking the funds for further education, he began a three-year apprenticeship as a woodturner under a guild master who was a friend of his late mother.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] The apprenticeship was harsh, involving long hours from early morning until evening with minimal pay and food.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] In February 1858, he became a journeyman turner and began his travels, working in various towns across southern Germany and Austria, including Heidelberg, Freiburg, Munich, and Salzburg.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] During his time in Freiburg, he joined a Catholic educational association for journeymen, one of many such clubs that provided moral and cultural guidance.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] This experience, along with contact with Christian socialist ideas, likely formed the basis for his early progressive thought.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] His travels ended on 7 May 1860, when he arrived in Leipzig, Saxony.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] There, he found employment with the master turner Julius Hahn, manufacturing door handles and billiard balls.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] When Bebel arrived in Leipzig in 1860, he was largely ignorant of politics and socialist theory.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] His initial concerns were personal and economic; he soon organized his fellow journeymen to successfully demand better meals and working conditions from their employer.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] Saxony's relatively liberal laws and Leipzig's status as a center of publishing and intellectual life provided fertile ground for the politicization of workers.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] On 19 February 1861, Bebel attended the founding meeting of the Leipzig *Arbeiterbildungsverein* (Workers' Educational Association), a club promoted by liberal democrats to provide general education to the working class.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] Initially aligned with the club's conservative, non-political majority, Bebel was elected to its executive committee.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] As late as 1863, he remained unconvinced of the need for general male suffrage, believing workers were not yet politically mature enough.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] The German workers' movement was soon split by the ideas of Ferdinand Lassalle, a charismatic lawyer who advocated for a workers' party independent of the liberal bourgeoisie.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] In the spring of 1862, a radical faction within the Leipzig association, influenced by Lassalle, demanded that the club adopt a political program centered on achieving universal direct suffrage.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] Bebel initially opposed this, but the club split, with the radical faction forming their own organization, the *Vorwärts* club.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] In May 1863, Lassalle founded the General German Workers' Association (ADAV) in Leipzig.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] Bebel and his associates in the educational associations, wary of Lassalle's pro-Prussian stance and authoritarian methods, founded a rival organization, the League of German Workers' Associations (VDAV), at a convention in Frankfurt in June 1863.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] The VDAV, initially guided by liberal-democratic principles, maintained a cultural-educational focus and remained aligned with the progressive bourgeois left.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] A decisive turn in Bebel's career came with his association with Wilhelm Liebknecht, a veteran of the 1848 revolutions and a disciple of Karl Marx, who had recently returned to Germany from exile in London.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] After Lassalle died in a duel in 1864, Liebknecht joined the VDAV and began to steer it toward Marxist principles.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] Bebel, strongly influenced by Liebknecht's intellect and revolutionary credentials, became his closest ally.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] After being expelled from Prussia in 1865, Liebknecht moved to Leipzig, where he and Bebel launched a campaign against the Lassalleans and their new leader, Johann Baptist von Schweitzer.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] By 1866, as many German liberals made peace with the Prussian state and the workers grew more suspicious of their bourgeois mentors, Bebel was converted to the principle of an independent workers' party.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] Together, Bebel and Liebknecht co-founded the Saxon People's Party in 1866, an anti-Prussian, democratic party that sought to unite working-class and lower-middle-class elements in a broad coalition against Prussian hegemony.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] In 1867, Bebel was elected as a deputy to the Reichstag of the new North German Confederation for the Glauchau-Meerane district, beginning his long parliamentary career.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] The growing political radicalism of Bebel and Liebknecht culminated in the founding of the Social Democratic Workers' Party of Germany (SDAP) at a congress in Eisenach from 7 to 9 August 1869.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] The new party, often called the "Eisenachers", was formed by a fusion of the VDAV with breakaway members of the ADAV under the leadership of Bebel and Liebknecht.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] Bebel was elected to the party's five-member Central Committee.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] The outbreak of the Franco-Prussian War in July 1870 placed Bebel and Liebknecht in a difficult position.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] While Marx and the Brunswick committee of the SDAP viewed the initial phase of the war as a legitimate defense of Germany against the aggression of Napoleon III, Bebel's opposition to the war was unwavering from the start.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] On 21 July 1870, Bebel and Liebknecht abstained from voting for war credits in the Reichstag, a compromise Bebel devised to avoid either supporting the Prussian government or appearing to favor Napoleon.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] This stance, though unpopular and opposed by the party executive, isolated the party from the wave of national enthusiasm that swept Germany.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] After the defeat of Napoleon III at the Battle of Sedan and the proclamation of the Third French Republic, Bebel and Liebknecht argued that the war was no longer defensive and voted against further war credits for the annexation of Alsace-Lorraine.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] They also expressed solidarity with the Paris Commune in 1871, which Bebel hailed in the Reichstag as a "preliminary skirmish" in the long campaign of the international working class.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] For their opposition to the war and alleged conspiracy to overthrow the state, Bebel, Liebknecht, and Adolf Hepner were arrested in December 1871 and tried for high treason in Leipzig in March 1872.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] Bebel used the trial as a platform to defend the principles of the SDAP.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] He and Liebknecht were convicted and sentenced to two years in a fortress prison (*Festungshaft*).
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] Bebel served his sentence in Hubertusburg, where he dedicated his time to study, reading works by Marx, Friedrich Engels, Charles Darwin, and others, and writing several pamphlets.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] The common struggle against the new German Empire brought the Lassalleans (ADAV) and the Eisenachers (SDAP) closer together.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] In May 1875, the two parties merged at a unity congress in Gotha to form the Socialist Workers' Party of Germany (SAPD).
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] Bebel played a key role in the unification, prioritizing the creation of a single, unified working-class party over doctrinal purity.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] The resulting Gotha Program was a compromise that incorporated Lassallean concepts such as state-aided cooperatives and the "iron law of wages", which drew a sharp critique from Marx and Engels.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] Bebel, who had tried but failed to prevent the inclusion of the "iron law", was privately annoyed by the harshness of the critique but remained confident in his ability to steer the new party in a Marxist direction.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] In 1878, two failed assassination attempts on Kaiser Wilhelm I by individuals with tenuous connections to socialism provided Chancellor Otto von Bismarck with a pretext to suppress the growing movement.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] Despite the SAPD's disavowal of the acts, Bismarck pushed the Anti-Socialist Law through the Reichstag in October 1878.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] The law banned all socialist organizations, meetings, and publications, forcing the party into illegality for the next twelve years.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] Party newspapers were suppressed, trade unions dissolved, and hundreds of activists arrested or expelled from their hometowns.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] During this "heroic era", Bebel emerged as the undisputed leader of the outlawed party.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] He assumed the duties of party treasurer and became the central organizer of the clandestine movement, maintaining contact with comrades throughout Germany and soliciting funds.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] The party's leadership was formally transferred to its Reichstag delegation, which remained a legal entity.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] Bebel used his parliamentary immunity to agitate against the government and maintain the party's public presence.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] He was instrumental in establishing the party's illegal newspaper, *Der Sozialdemokrat*, which was smuggled into Germany from Zurich and served as the movement's organizational and ideological center.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] At the secret party congress at Wyden, Switzerland, in 1880, Bebel successfully led the move to expel the anarchist faction led by Johann Most and Wilhelm Hasselmann, thereby preserving the party's commitment to a political, rather than terrorist, strategy.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] He formed a major political relationship with Paul Singer, who replaced Liebknecht as Bebel's "right-hand man" in the party leadership from the late 1880s until Singer's death in 1911.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] The Anti-Socialist Law lapsed on 30 September 1890.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] The SAPD emerged from persecution stronger than ever, winning 1.4 million votes and 35 Reichstag seats in the February 1890 election, a triumph that contributed to Bismarck's dismissal by the new emperor, Wilhelm II.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] Bebel now led the work of reorganizing the party on a legal basis.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] At the Halle Congress in 1890, the party was renamed the Social Democratic Party of Germany (SPD), and a new, decentralized organizational structure was adopted to navigate the remaining restrictive state laws.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] At the Erfurt Congress in 1891, the party adopted a new program drafted primarily by Karl Kautsky and Eduard Bernstein.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] The Erfurt Program was a thoroughly Marxist document, affirming the inevitability of the collapse of capitalism and the necessity of the working class conquering political power.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] Bebel defended the program, which became a model for socialist parties across Europe.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] During the 1890s, Bebel consolidated his leadership against challenges from both the left and the right.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] He defeated the radical *Jungen* ("Youths"), who criticized the party's parliamentary focus, and began to confront the growing influence of reformist tendencies, particularly from the South German party organizations led by Georg von Vollmar.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] At the 1895 Breslau party congress, Bebel suffered a rare defeat when his support for an agrarian program designed to attract peasant voters was overwhelmingly rejected in favor of a resolution from Kautsky and Clara Zetkin that defended the party's strict proletarian purity.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] The most significant internal challenge came from the rise of Revisionism, a theoretical movement initiated by Eduard Bernstein.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] Bebel led the orthodox Marxist counter-attack.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] While privately acknowledging the need for practical reforms, he insisted that the party's revolutionary goal—the *Kladderadatsch*, or great collapse of capitalism—was essential for its identity and unity.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] With constant goading from Bebel, Kautsky became the chief theoretical opponent of revisionism.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] At successive party congresses, most notably at Hanover (1899) and Dresden (1903), Bebel marshaled the party majority to condemn Revisionism in principle, while avoiding an open split by allowing revisionists to remain in the party.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] At the Dresden congress, Bebel used all his influence to line up delegates behind the party leadership's grand condemnation of revisionism, cementing a temporary alliance between the party executive and the radicals.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] In the last decade of his life, Bebel's attention was increasingly consumed by internal party struggles and the growing threats of militarism and war.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] The Russian Revolution of 1905 sparked a major debate within the SPD over the use of the political mass strike.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] While the party's radical wing, led by Rosa Luxemburg, saw it as a crucial revolutionary weapon, the trade union leaders were strongly opposed.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] At the Jena Congress in 1905, in a marathon three-and-a-half-hour address, Bebel engineered a compromise.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] He framed the revolution as a defensive act and recommended the mass strike primarily as a defensive weapon to protect existing rights, such as universal suffrage, rather than as a tool for revolutionary change.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] At the Mannheim Congress in 1906, under pressure from the powerful trade unions, Bebel performed a "masterpiece of rhetoric and leadership" by executing a tactical retreat.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] He shepherded through the Mannheim Agreement, which established formal parity between the party and the unions, and effectively gave the union leadership a veto over any future use of the mass strike.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] Bebel's foreign policy views were dominated by a deep-seated Russophobia and a growing concern for Germany's diplomatic isolation.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] He viewed Tsarist Russia as the primary threat to European peace and the German workers' movement.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] While consistently opposing German militarism and naval expansion as a threat to peace with Britain, he repeatedly affirmed that the SPD would defend the fatherland in a war against Russian aggression.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] He took a hard line against radical anti-militarism within the party, raising Karl Liebknecht's proposal for an anti-militarist youth campaign to an issue of confidence at the Mannheim congress and mocking comparisons with the Belgian and French socialists as irrelevant.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] At the 1907 Essen Congress, during the "Noske debates" on the party's response to its recent electoral defeat, Bebel argued that the party sought to democratize the army not to weaken it, but to strengthen national defense, even advocating for compulsory pre-military training for youth.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] This patriotic stance marked a significant step in the party's integration into the national state and foreshadowed the SPD's position in 1914.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] Bebel's health, never robust, declined sharply in his final years.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] He suffered from heart disease and recurring bronchial problems.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] The death of his wife Julie from cancer in November 1910 was a severe blow, followed by the death of his son-in-law Ferdinand Simon and the mental breakdown of his daughter Frieda in 1912.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] Despite his failing health, he remained the party's paramount leader, proposing Hugo Haase to succeed the late Paul Singer as co-chairman in 1911.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] In 1912, the SPD won a massive electoral victory, capturing 110 seats to become the largest party in the Reichstag.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] Bebel, who was absent during the negotiations, had "serious worries" about the secret electoral pact with the Progressive Party that helped secure the victory.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] Bebel died of a heart attack on 13 August 1913, while visiting a sanatorium in Passug, Switzerland.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] His body was taken to Zurich, which he had chosen as his second home.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] His funeral was a massive international event, attended by tens of thousands of workers and socialist leaders from across Europe, including Jean Jaurès and Victor Adler.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] His ashes were interred next to those of his wife in Zurich.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] In 1866, Bebel married Johanna Carolina Henrietta Otto, known as Julie, a milliner and the daughter of a railroad worker.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] Their marriage was described as happy and supportive, with Julie providing Bebel with political and economic advice throughout his career.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] They had one child, a daughter named Bertha Friederika (1869–1948), called Frieda.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] Ferdinand Simon, a physician and socialist from Breslau, with whom Bebel maintained a close relationship.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] Bebel began his career as a self-employed master turner in Leipzig in 1864.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] His business initially struggled due to his political activities, which repelled middle-class customers, and his imprisonment in 1872 nearly led to bankruptcy.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] In the late 1870s, he took on a business partner, Ferdinand Issleib, who put the enterprise on a firm financial footing.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] Later in life, royalties from his highly successful book *Woman and Socialism*, combined with a substantial inheritance from a political admirer in 1903, made him a wealthy man.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] August Bebel was the most important leader of the German Social Democratic movement for nearly half a century.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] More than any other figure, he embodied the party's identity and was revered by the working-class masses as their "shadow emperor" (*Schattenkaiser*).
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] He was a powerful orator, a master politician who dominated party congresses, and a pragmatic tactician who successfully guided the SPD from a small sect into the largest political party in Germany.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] While remaining personally committed to the revolutionary goals of Marxism, his practical work in the Reichstag laid the groundwork for the SPD's evolution into a reformist party.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] Both the Social Democratic Party of the Federal Republic of Germany and the Socialist Unity Party of the German Democratic Republic later claimed him as a forefather.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] His most famous work, *Woman and Socialism* (*Die Frau und der Sozialismus*), published in 1879, was a groundbreaking analysis of the oppression of women from a Marxist perspective.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] It went through more than fifty editions by 1914, was translated into numerous languages, and became one of the most widely read socialist texts of its time, establishing Bebel as a central figure in the socialist feminist movement.
[src:august-bebel/august-bebel] His multi-volume autobiography, *Aus meinem Leben* (*From My Life*), is a major source for the history of the German socialist movement.
